</paragraph>
<paragraph id="940D9A4BFFF4FFA58748FB1E48B6FB01" blockId="79.[264,1323,1233,1819]" box="[264,387,1233,1258]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA58748FB1E48B6FB01" box="[264,387,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="940D9A4BFFF4FFA58778FB364BE0F8F0" blockId="79.[264,1323,1233,1819]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="4B0924E9FFF4FFA58479FB364B5EFAF8" box="[569,619,1273,1299]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation id="0C8986CEFFF4FFA5849AFB364A0EFAF8" box="[730,827,1273,1299]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="82.[264,367,1514,1538]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,314,1490]" captionTargetId="figure-136@82.[264,1323,314,1490]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="FIGURE 23. Habitats of larvae of Hebridosimulium species, Vanuatu. a. Santo, Sarakata River, UNELCO Hydro Station. Type locality of S. callipygium. Note limestone substrate. b. Santo, Upper Sarakata River, Millennium Cave region. Typical habitat of S. callipygium and S. subparadisium. c. Malekula, Wesso River, downstream of cascade. Type locality of S. spiroi. Note travertine substrate. d. Banks Islands, Vanua Lava, Tahiti River. Type locality of S. banksi and S. undulatum. e. Tanna, stream south of Bethel. Type locality of S. johnfrumi. f. Malekula, Pankumu River. Type locality of S. pankumuense. g. Efate, Ewor River, La Cressionnière. Type locality of S. tuberculum. Note the travertine terraces." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071447/files/figure.png" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Fig. 23c</figureCitation>
) on Malekula, larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="53B2E1C8FFF4FFA58218FB364D8DFAF9" authorityName="Craig, Currie &amp; Hunter" authorityYear="2006" box="[1112,1208,1273,1298]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiroi">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA58218FB364D8DFAF9" box="[1112,1208,1273,1298]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">S. spiroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appear to be habitat specialists. They were taken in moderately large numbers only from smooth travertine substrate in fast flow (
<quantity id="534A37AEFFF4FFA584C6FA864BF8FA88" box="[646,717,1353,1379]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" unit="m" value="1.3">1.3 m</quantity>
/s; Table 1). However, larvae exhibit little structural adaptation to that habitat beyond the scarcely steatopygous abdomen and a relatively large number of hooks in the posterior circlet. Superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="53B2E1C8FFF4FFA58221FA564C37FA59" authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[1121,1282,1433,1458]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adsonense">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA58221FA564C37FA59" box="[1121,1282,1433,1458]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">S. adsonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in possessing a darkly pigmented larval head and lighter coloured body (
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA58205FA0E4D6CFA31" box="[1093,1113,1473,1498]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">rf</emphasis>
. 
<figureCitation id="0C8986CEFFF4FFA58228FA0E4DCBFA30" box="[1128,1278,1473,1499]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="28.[264,367,1774,1798]" captionTargetBox="[265,1322,406,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-68@28.[265,1322,406,1750]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 11. Left lateral views of Hebridosimulium species larvae. Last-instar larvae, except l &amp; n, which are penultimate. Arrowheads indicate dorsal tubercles. Scale bar = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071417" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071417/files/figure.png" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
Figs. 
<quantity id="534A37AEFFF4FFA582EAFA0E4DEAFA30" box="[1194,1247,1473,1499]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" unit="m" value="11.0">11m</quantity>
, n
</figureCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="53B2E1C8FFF4FFA58354FA0E487EF9E9" authorityName="Craig, Currie &amp; Hunter" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiroi">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA58354FA0E487EF9E9" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">S. spiroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the structure of the pupal gill filaments (cf. 
<figureCitation id="0C8986CEFFF4FFA58584FA264D7EF9E8" box="[964,1099,1513,1539]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[264,367,1531,1555]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,326,1507]" captionTargetId="figure-95@27.[264,1323,326,1507]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Pupal gill filaments of Hebridosimulium species (continued). Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071415" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071415/files/figure.png" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Figs. 10e, f</figureCitation>
), size and shape of the postgenal cleft, and markedly larger hypostomal teeth. Although grouped together with 
<taxonomicName id="53B2E1C8FFF4FFA58748F9F648ABF9B9" authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[264,414,1593,1618]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adsonense">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA58748F9F648ABF9B9" box="[264,414,1593,1618]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">S. adsonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Malekula, we are of the opinion that the body shape and the head colour in both species may be independent adaptations to full sunlight in shallow, fast water. Dark pigmentation of larval heads is a known adaptation to full insolation (
<bibRefCitation id="F023E7BAFFF4FFA58222F9464DD9F948" author="Craig, D. A." box="[1122,1260,1673,1699]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="855 - 904" refId="ref41323" refString="Craig, D. A. (1997) A taxonomic revision of the Pacific black fly subgenus Inseliellum (Diptera: Simuliidae). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 75, 855 - 904." type="journal article" year="1997">Craig 1997</bibRefCitation>
) and most likely is protective against UV light (
<bibRefCitation id="F023E7BAFFF4FFA58541F97E4D7EF920" author="Donahue, W. F. &amp; Schindler, D. W." box="[769,1099,1713,1739]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" pagination="357 - 365" refId="ref42015" refString="Donahue, W. F. &amp; Schindler, D. W. (1998) Diel emigration and colonization responses by black flies (Diptera: Simuliidae) to ultraviolet radiation. Freshwater Biology, 40, 357 - 365." type="journal article" year="1998">Donahue &amp; Schindler 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Preliminary CO1 mitochondrial DNA analysis indicates that 
<taxonomicName id="53B2E1C8FFF4FFA5854CF9164A5AF919" authorityName="Craig, Currie &amp; Hunter" authorityYear="2006" box="[780,879,1753,1778]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spiroi">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA5854CF9164A5AF919" box="[780,879,1753,1778]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">S. spiroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="53B2E1C8FFF4FFA585ECF9164D70F919" authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[940,1093,1753,1778]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="79" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adsonense">
<emphasis id="A6C64659FFF4FFA585ECF9164D70F919" box="[940,1093,1753,1778]" italics="true" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">S. adsonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not genetically close (A. Cywinska, unpublished data).
</paragraph>
